), or 0.105 m.

The momentum of an object is the product of its mass and its velocity. The impulse of a force is the product of the force’s average value and the time during which the force acts. The Impulse-Momentum Theorem relates these parameters (in terms of the effects of a force exerted on an object) by stating that the impulse of a force is equal to the change in momentum of the object to which the force is applied (
Cutnell and Johnson, 1992
).

The Work-Energy Theorem (
Cutnell and Johnson, 1992
) states that the work done on an object by a net force is equal to the change in kinetic energy of the object caused by the net force. Given that the kinetic energy ofa moving object is equal to (mass x velocity2)/ 2, we can apply the Work-Energy Theorem to the second, sliding phase of the fall of our animal as
